SIMPLE: formation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Formation
<hw>For*ma"tion</hw> <pr>(f⟦ocr⟧r*m⟦amac⟧"sh⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[L. <ets>formatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>formation</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of giving form or shape to anything; a forming;
a shaping.</def> <rj><au>Beattie.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The manner in which a thing is formed; structure;
construction; conformation; form; <as>as, the peculiar
<ex>formation</ex> of the heart</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A substance formed or deposited.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Mineral deposits and
rock masses designated with reference to their origin; <as>as, the
siliceous <ex>formation</ex> about geysers; alluvial
<ex>formations</ex>; marine <ex>formations</ex>.</as></def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>A group of beds of the same age or period; <as>as, the Eocene
<ex>formation</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>The arrangement of a body of
troops, as in a square, column, etc.</def> <rj><au>Farrow.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Formative</ent>⟦br⟧
